  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game centers on trading red and green chips with asymmetric private values for red and common values for green. Green chips are worth $0.50 to everyone and are known to be common-value. Red chips are privately valued at $0.30 by Otter and Goose, but at $0.80 by Badger. All start at 10 red and 10 green, so Badger begins with the strongest incentive to acquire red chips from others and to shed green only if she gets sufficiently underpriced red in return. Otter and Goose, who value red less, have an incentive to sell red for green at favorable rates, but will be cautious not to give away too much surplus if they suspect others may value red more. Because each player only knows their own red valuation, the key uncertainty is about how much the others value red relative to green. This creates an inference problem: generous red-for-green offers might signal that someone values red highly, while a reluctance to buy red could signal a low private red value. At the same time, over three short rounds there is limited time to fully learn the others’ values.\n\nGiven the personas, all three are inequality-tolerant and not strongly punitive, so they are less likely to walk away from positive-surplus trades simply to avoid unequal outcomes. Otter and Goose are both reflective and socially attuned, which makes them more likely to experiment with modest, interpretable offers early to test the waters without large exposure. Badger, as the high-red-value player, has strong economic motives to accumulate red: every red she moves from Otter or Goose into her own pile yields an extra $0.50 of private value relative to its value to them. Rationally, she should try to buy red using green (which is only worth $0.50 to everyone) at rates like 1 green for 2 or even 3 red; these trades are profitable for her and, if structured reasonably, remain privately profitable for low-red-value partners as well.\n\nStrategically, early in the game we expect: (1) simple, near-fair-looking trades from Otter and Goose that do not require precise beliefs about others’ red values; and (2) more aggressive red-acquisition attempts from Badger, possibly probing how cheaply she can buy red. Any accepted trades slightly change the chip distribution and may act as soft signals about values. Because acceptances are private and chosen simultaneously, each responder must weigh the immediate private gain against the risk of being exploited if the rate is too unfavorable. Over the three rounds, the likely dynamic is that at least one red-acquisition trade by Badger gets accepted, leading to a final distribution where Badger holds somewhat more red and fewer green, and at least one of Otter or Goose holds more green and fewer red, while the other may remain closer to the starting allocation if they are more cautious or unlucky with timing and competition for the same offer.",
