 the number of green chips she holds without adequate red compensation, but not especially vengeful.\n\nThe main dynamic uncertainty: (1) Will ram realize her red is relatively low-value compared to green? (2) Will otter/squid correctly infer ram is willing to sell red once they see her patterns of acceptance and proposals? (3) How will competition between otter and squid for ram’s red play out, given that if they both accept a good offer from ram, a random lottery chooses the actual trade partner? This competition can encourage slightly more generous terms from ram to attract acceptance but must be balanced against her desire not to overpay.\n\nAcross 3 rounds, each player gets one proposal per round, so 9 total turns. Because chip endowments are symmetric at the start (10 red, 10 green each) and there is limited time, players are likely to test a few different exchange rates early and converge toward more favorable but still acceptably fair-looking ones. Otter and squid, valuing red highly, will try to acquire extra red from at least one other player, ideally ram. Ram, valuing red far less, will try to transform red into green but must act under incomplete information about how attractive red is to the others. Over the game, we should see an early exploratory phase (round 0), a mid-game adjustment and more decisive red-for-green exchanges (round 1), and a final push in round 2 where remaining red held by ram is sold off at exchange rates that reflect improved mutual inference about relative values.",
