gical reasoner. He values RED similarly to pig. He is more willing than turtle to accept slightly uneven trades if they seem cooperative and not too costly. But he still aims to increase his own value, so he will not consistently accept bad deals.\n\nStrategically, players want to turn relatively low-value RED chips into higher-value GREEN chips where possible, but they face uncertainty about others’ private values and face a random-recipient rule when multiple responders accept. That rule means a proposer cannot target the best partner; if both responders like the deal, the realized partner is random. This discourages extremely skewed proposals that might cause a race to accept and instead encourages trades that at least one other player finds clearly positive without being obviously exploitable to both.\n\nWith only three rounds and exactly one proposal per player per round, there is limited time for learning. Early proposals will be more exploratory: players float offers that reflect their own valuations and see who bites. Later rounds can adjust based on observed acceptances and rejections. Given the values, analysts expect occasional RED-for-GREEN trades at somewhat generous rates for the party giving up GREEN, particularly between turtle (who undervalues RED) and the other two (who value RED more). However, turtle’s guardedness and the others’ awareness that GREEN is highly valuable can lead to several declined offers when proposers push for too much GREEN in exchange for RED.\n\nOverall bargaining dynamics: pig and elephant are somewhat aligned in valuations and moderate in caution, so trades among them are more likely if they offer near-even deals in value terms. Turtle is an outlier with very low RED value and high exploitation caution; he will push for trades that give him GREEN and shed RED but is unlikely to accept expensive RED-for-GREEN deals. Uncertainty about others’ RED valuations and the random-recipient rule introduce noise; some offers that would