. Dog is empathic, socially adaptive, with medium cooperation and moderate exploitation caution; she is likely to avoid obviously disadvantageous trades but may agree to mildly unequal offers if they feel socially reasonable and provide some gain. Butterfly is a strong logical reasoner, fairly cooperation-oriented, and behaviorally stable, suggesting he will quickly parse value implications and aim for trades that are at least weakly improving, with some willingness to accept deals that look rational even if not perfectly fair.\n\nThe main strategic tension centers on the random recipient rule: if more than one responder accepts a proposal, the executed partner is chosen at random. This weakens targeted favoritism and creates risk for responders: an acceptance is only worthwhile in expectation. Proposers must craft offers that are attractive to at least one partner but not so generous that both are very likely to accept unless the proposer is indifferent about who trades. Early in the game, players will tentatively test the market—especially around buying valued RED from dog in exchange for GREEN or BLUE. As offers are accepted or rejected, players update beliefs: for instance, a player who sees dog eagerly trade RED for GREEN infers that dog likely values RED relatively low. Given only three rounds (nine total proposals), we expect limited but nontrivial reallocation of RED from dog toward butterfly and possibly ram, some BLUE shifting from dog toward ram/butterfly, and modest use of GREEN to grease these trades. Because ram moves first every round, he has repeated chances to set a structured pattern and subtly exploit his higher chip values, while butterfly’s reasoning skill makes him a likely active counterparty when he sees positive-sum terms.\n\nThe forecasted play below assumes that: (1) each player respects the rule constraints, (2) they use simple expected-value reasoning guided by their own valuations, (3) they remain somewhat conservative under uncertainty, and (4) their persona-driven tendencies shape how generous or demanding their proposals are, and which approximate, slightly unequal trades they deem acceptable.",
