  "game_explanation": "This three-player chip-bargaining game features privately known values for red, blue, and purple chips, with green chips having a common and publicly known value of $0.50 for everyone. Each player starts with 10 of each color and has three rounds (nine proposal turns total) to trade bilaterally. Because only one chip type can be bought and one sold per proposal, and responders act simultaneously without direct communication, players must infer others’ values from observed offers and acceptances, and they face uncertainty about which of multiple acceptors (if any) will be matched.\n\nIncentives are strongly shaped by the heterogeneous valuations:\n- buffalo-yellow-4552 (Buffalo) values BLUE the most ($1.00) and PURPLE next ($0.70), with GREEN at $0.50 and RED relatively weak at $0.30. Buffalo should want to accumulate BLUE and PURPLE and be willing to give up RED first, then possibly GREEN, if the tradeoff is favorable.\n- goose-green-9189 (Goose) values RED the most ($0.90), then PURPLE ($0.70), then BLUE ($0.80), with GREEN at $0.50. Goose is the strongest RED buyer and has mid–high values for BLUE and PURPLE, so Goose is generally willing to pay GREEN or low-value colors (from Goose’s perspective) for RED, provided the price is not too bad.\n- bear-red-8738 (Bear) has relatively low valuations for BLUE ($0.20) and PURPLE ($0.20), with RED at $0.40 and GREEN at $0.50. Bear is naturally inclined to dump BLUE and PURPLE and to buy GREEN or, secondarily, RED if the price is attractive.\n\nSurplus potentials: win–win trades exist mainly where a chip is strong for the buyer and weak for the seller. Examples:\n- RED from Bear to Goose can create surplus because Goose values RED at $0.90 and Bear at $0.40.\n- BLUE from Bear to Buffalo can create surplus because Buffalo values BLUE at $1.00 and Bear at $0.20.\n- PURPLE from Bear to Buffalo or Goose can also be mutually beneficial.\n- GREEN is common-value, so there is no pure value gap on GREEN. However, GREEN may still function as a medium of exchange if players reason that others treat GREEN as a safe baseline and will trade away other colors for it.\n\nUncertainty and inference: each player only knows their own values and the public common-value of GREEN, but not others’ private values. Early in the game, they may make conservative, roughly “fair-looking” offers using GREEN as a stable reference (e.g., exchanging RED or BLUE for GREEN at roughly one-for-one or modestly imbalanced ratios) to probe others’ interest without seeming exploitative. Over time, acceptance patterns help them infer who especially wants RED, BLUE, or PURPLE: repeated acceptance of offers to buy RED, for example, signals a high RED value.\n\nPersona-modulated behavior:\n- Buffalo is empathic and structure-seeking, with medium cooperation and exploitation caution. She is likely to make reasonably balanced, clearly structured offers early, preferring predictability and not wanting to risk obvious exploitation or rejection. She may try to use GREEN as a clean numeraire.\n- Goose is analytically strong and somewhat guarded (high exploitation caution, low norm enforcement). Goose will search for positive-value trades, especially to stock up on RED, but may drive a harder bargain and be hesitant to overpay, especially early. However, with strong reasoning skills and longer time horizon, Goose can adapt quickly from observed responses.\n- Bear is a strong reasoner, high in cooperation but inequality-tolerant and with low norm enforcement. Bear is willing to accept quite unequal trades if they still leave Bear ahead in dollar terms and may accept deals others would reject, especially when moving from low-value BLUE/PURPLE into higher-value GREEN or RED.\n\nStrategic dynamics across rounds:\n- Round 0 will likely feature exploratory, relatively modest offers using GREEN as payment or as the thing bought, seeking signals about counterpart valuations. One or two early trades may execute if someone with a clearly lower value for a chip meets someone who strongly wants it.\n- Round 1 sees players updating beliefs from Round 0. Those who succeeded in a trade may push similar patterns; those whose offers failed may adjust prices or targeted colors. If someone has revealed demand (e.g., evident interest in RED), counterparts can begin to extract a small premium while still leaving positive surplus.\n- Round 2 is the final opportunity; players should be more willing to make sharper, more value-driven offers (less “fair” in appearance) to lock in gains, especially if they’ve identified specific win–win directions. Some may accept borderline trades they would have rejected earlier, because unused bargaining power has no future value.\n\nAcross the full game, Buffalo’s best path is to trade away RED (and possibly some GREEN) for BLUE and PURPLE, particularly from Bear (who values those colors low). Goose’s best path is to accumulate RED, often from Bear, perhaps paying in GREEN or in colors Goose values less. Bear’s best path is to unload BLUE and PURPLE in exchange for GREEN (and maybe RED), likely to Buffalo and Goose respectively. We forecast that several deals will execute along those lines, though not perfectly optimized, because each player faces uncertainty about others’ valuations and must infer them from a small number of noisy signals within just three rounds.",
