PURPLE more than Alligator; Alligator can offload PURPLE to Owl if compensated in BLUE/RED.\n- Alligator vs Ram: Alligator loves BLUE/RED; Ram loves RED and is neutral among other colors. There is less dramatic misalignment except on BLUE (0.90 vs 0.50) and PURPLE (0.30 vs 0.50). Gains exist but are smaller.\n\nLikely dynamics:\n- Owl’s proposals: Numerically small, rate-like exchanges that offload BLUE for higher-valued chips. She will tend to avoid big gambles, especially early in the game.\n- Alligator’s proposals: Bolder, more value-exploitative trades, especially trying to acquire RED and BLUE quickly from Ram and Owl by paying with PURPLE or sometimes GREEN. Because of low norm enforcement, he may push offers that are just barely acceptable or slightly unfair.\n- Ram’s proposals: Simpler, value-stable offers that trade less-valued colors for RED. He will usually avoid blatantly unequal trades and may anchor around 1:1 or 2:1 intuitive fairness.\n\nUncertainty and learning: Because players do not know others’ private values, each accepted/declined offer provides information. Rejections of seemingly generous trades might reveal that the recipient also values the sought chip highly. The limited 3-round horizon reduces scope for long-run reputation building; players are more myopic, especially Alligator. The random-recipient rule when multiple players accept weakens targeted bilateral deals: proposers must design offers that they are comfortable executing with either potential recipient.\n\nGiven these priors, we can forecast a path where Owl starts cautiously, Alligator quickly exploits BLUE / PURPLE mispricings, and Ram focuses on exchanging low-priority colors for RED while preserving intuitive fairness. Early trades are small and exploratory; later ones are more aggressive and value-exploitative as players infer who seems keen on which colors.",
