iffer on the ranking of red, blue, and purple. Early in the game, trades double as signals: if someone offers to give up a lot of a color, others infer that color is probably low-value for the sender. Because there are only three rounds (nine total proposals), players have limited time to experiment and learn. Given the personalities, butterfly and cat are more willing to make slightly generous but still positive-EV offers early to establish mutually beneficial exchange patterns, while badger will accept only clearly profitable offers and propose conservative deals that offload his low-value blue and possibly green in return for purple or red. Over the three rounds, we can expect (a) directional sorting where badger accumulates purple, cat accumulates blue, and butterfly moves toward red/purple at the cost of blue/green, and (b) a few declined offers when proposed prices are too aggressive or misaligned with others’ hidden values.",
