parently generous offer is actually equal or even exploitative from the other’s perspective.\n- Multiple acceptance risk: When a proposer makes an attractive offer for a chip color that more than one responder values, both might accept, and the partner is then chosen at random. Proposers can’t target a specific partner, so they must design offers that are safe (i.e., profitable or at least acceptable) no matter which responder ends up trading.\n\nLikely bargaining dynamics:\n- Early in the game (Round 0), players are exploring: they expect others to value green, and they suspect some variation on red/blue/purple. Proposals will be one-step “value trades,” like offering RED for GREEN or BLUE, where the sender offloads a chip they probably value less.\n- Mid-game (Round 1), after seeing which offers are accepted or rejected, players infer rough preferences: e.g., if Owl eagerly trades away RED for BLUE, others infer that Owl likes BLUE. This shapes later proposals: more targeted offers that give others something they seem to want, while capturing surplus.\n- Late game (Round 2), players anticipate the end. They are more willing to accept modestly beneficial trades because there is no future opportunity to improve further, and they may ignore long-run reputation or fairness. Surplus-increasing trades that are slightly unbalanced in favor of the proposer can still be accepted if they clearly improve the responder’s payoff.\n\nOverall, we expect:\n- BLUE to drift toward Owl and Butterfly, especially Owl.\n- PURPLE to drift toward Ram and Owl from Butterfly.\n- RED to drift away from Butterfly toward Ram/Owl, especially when paired with GREEN or BLUE.\n- GREEN to serve as a safe anchor everyone is willing to trade around, but no one wants to give up cheaply.\n\nGiven the personas, Butterfly will propose cautiously beneficial trades and accept only clearly favorable ones. Ram will propose reasonably fair, efficiency-increasing trades and is relatively easy to recruit as a 