  "game_explanation": "This three-player, three-round bargaining game has privately known values for red, blue, and purple chips, and a common known value for green chips ($0.50 each). All players start with 10 of each chip, so the initial dollar value of any color is symmetric given the public range, but privately there are strong differences in which colors are most valuable. Each player wants to maximize their own final portfolio value in dollars, not the total group surplus. Because trades are bilateral but acceptance is simultaneous and random when multiple players accept, proposers must design offers that (a) are appealing enough to attract at least one counterparty, but (b) do not give away too much surplus, and (c) are robust to the fact that the specific accepting partner cannot be chosen if there is competition. Uncertainty arises from hidden chip values and from the possibility that multiple players accept a particularly advantageous offer. Given the values, duck-green-5428 values red ($1.00) and purple ($0.80) most; alligator-orange-1621 values purple ($0.80) and blue ($0.60); and dolphin-pink-1017 values red ($0.80) and blue ($0.40) most. Green is equal for all. Rational, value-driven bargaining suggests that dolphin will mostly try to trade away her very low-value purple for red or blue; duck will try to accumulate red and purple while parting with green or (to a lesser extent) blue; and alligator will try to trade red away in exchange for purple or blue. However, during play they only know their own valuations and must infer others’ relative values from observed offers and acceptances. Personas imply all three are cooperation-oriented and at least moderately cautious about exploitation. So they are likely to propose trades that seem fair in nominal terms (small or roughly balanced quantities) early on, updating based on who accepts what. Over three rounds, each player only gets three proposal turns, so there is limited time to explore and then exploit. Early turns are exploratory and conservative, testing the market. Later turns, once some pattern of responses is observed, are more targeted: players shift to offers that convert their low-value chips into high-value chips even if that means offering generous terms to ensure acceptance before the game ends. Because acceptance is simultaneous and random when multiple players agree, players may avoid extremely generous offers that would invite competition, or they may embrace that randomness if any counterparty is fine so long as they exchange low-value for high-value chips. Overall, we expect moderate, incremental trades, no extreme windfalls, gradual learning about others’ preferences, and some trades that improve both sides’ values given the complementarity of their private valuations.",
