  "game_explanation": "This 4-chip bargaining game creates overlapping but asymmetric interests. Green chips are common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so they are a natural unit of account and a baseline 'safe' asset. Red, blue, and purple chips differ in value across players and are privately known during play, which creates both gains-from-trade opportunities and uncertainty about what others value.\n\nTotal private values per chip type:\n- kangaroo-red-5113: BLUE $0.30, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.90, RED $0.40\n- frog-orange-8868: BLUE $0.80, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.20, RED $0.50\n- unicorn-yellow-3690: BLUE $0.30, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.10, RED $0.50\n\nAcross the group (summing values):\n- RED: kangaroo 0.40 + frog 0.50 + unicorn 0.50 = 1.40\n- BLUE: kangaroo 0.30 + frog 0.80 + unicorn 0.30 = 1.40\n- PURPLE: kangaroo 0.90 + frog 0.20 + unicorn 0.10 = 1.20\n- GREEN: all 0.50\nSo red and blue have highest social surplus; purple is particularly valuable to kangaroo; frog uniquely values blue highly; kangaroo uniquely values purple highly. Red is slightly more valuable than green to frog and unicorn; purple is almost worthless to unicorn and low for frog.\n\nIncentives:\n- kangaroo-benefits a lot from acquiring purple (0.90) and somewhat from keeping purple and trading away relatively low-value blue (0.30) or possibly some red (0.40) if she can get green or purple. She is cooperation-oriented but not strongly punitive, with high behavioral stability and patience, so she is likely to aim for clearly positive personal gains and avoid very risky or exploitative offers.\n- frog-has a strong private advantage for blue (0.80) versus others (0.30), and only mild advantage for red. He will try converting green, purple, or even some red into blue at favorable rates. Being reflective and stable, frog likely constructs trades that yield clear expected gains while not being so skewed that they are always rejected.\n- unicorn-views red (0.50) and green (0.50) as equal, blue and purple as low (0.30, 0.10). He is inequality-tolerant and structure-seeking, so he is willing to accept slightly uneven deals if they are simple, predictable, and clearly profitable in his own values.\n\nStrategic uncertainties:\n- Each player knows only their own values, so they must infer others' preferences from which offers are made and accepted. For example, frog will suspect others value blue less if they are willing to give it up cheaply, while kangaroo will reveal a strong purple valuation if she keeps rejecting purple-for-other-color trades.\n- Simultaneous responses and random partner selection when multiple accept introduce risk: a proposer cannot target a specific counterpart. Offers must be acceptable enough that at least one other player is willing to accept, but not so generous that both accept when the proposer strongly prefers one recipient over the other.\n- With only 3 rounds (9 total proposal turns), players face a short horizon, so they can not rely heavily on reputational strategies. However, their stable and somewhat cooperative profiles mean they will still seek reasonable mutual gains instead of pure exploitation.\n\nLikely dynamics over the full game:\n- Early in round 0, offers will be exploratory and slightly conservative: simple one-color-for-one-color or two-for-one style trades involving green and red or blue. Players test the waters about what others will accept. Because players start with symmetric holdings (10 of each color) and equal green value, initial trades often involve changing the mix between red, blue, and purple at mild exchange rates.\n- Once frog recognizes that others may trade blue away (worth 0.30 to them) in exchange for green or red (worth 0.50 to unicorn and frog), he can push for favorable blue-acquisition trades. Kangaroo, seeing her strong purple value, may try to buy purple with blue or possibly green, but she will avoid paying more than roughly 2:1 in her own value terms.\n- Unicorn is happy to give up purple (0.10) or some blue (0.30) for red (0.50) or green (0.50), especially in simple, low-friction trades. He is less focused on punishing unfairness and more on obtaining predictable improvements, so moderate but clear gains will usually be accepted.\n- Across rounds 1 and 2, successful early trades will steer the later bargaining: if, for example, frog has already concentrated a lot of blue, he may shift toward trading away small quantities of blue for red or green only when marginal gains are still positive. Kangaroo may end in a purple-heavy portfolio, and unicorn in a red/green-heavy one.\n\nGiven the players' moderate cooperation and stability, many offers will be designed so the responder gains in their own valuation while the proposer gains even more. Declines will mostly occur when one side perceives a clearly negative expected value or when uncertainty about others' valuations makes a trade seem too risky, especially early on. The forecast below follows that logic, constructing a plausible full game path of offers and acceptances consistent with payoffs, uncertainty, and the provided personas.",
