  "game_explanation": "This 3-player, 3-round chip bargaining game features privately known values for red, blue, and purple chips, with green chips as a common-value currency at $0.50 each. Each player starts with 10 of each color. The key strategic driver is that trades must involve swapping different colors, and all chips are divisible only in whole units.\n\nCore private values:\n- Squid (squid-red-8346): BLUE $0.40, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.70, RED $0.60. Squid’s ranking: PURPLE (0.70) > RED (0.60) > GREEN (0.50) > BLUE (0.40). Squid is moderately prosocial but strongly exploitation-cautious and structure-seeking; he will look for clearly positive deals and avoid ambiguous ones.\n- Alligator (alligator-yellow-2825): BLUE $1.00, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.20, RED $0.90. Alligator’s ranking: BLUE (1.00) > RED (0.90) >> GREEN (0.50) >> PURPLE (0.20). She is empathic, generosity-forward, and less focused on punishing unfairness, so she will sometimes offer counterparties good deals if they look mutually beneficial or cooperative.\n- Peacock (peacock-yellow-3297): BLUE $0.80, GREEN $0.50, PURPLE $0.90, RED $0.10. Peacock’s ranking: PURPLE (0.90) > BLUE (0.80) >> GREEN (0.50) >>> RED (0.10). He is reflective and cooperation-oriented but with some norm-enforcement; he is willing to make and accept balanced or slightly favorable trades but resists clearly lopsided ones.\n\nMajor incentive patterns:\n- Red chips: Very valuable to Squid (0.60) and especially Alligator (0.90), nearly worthless to Peacock (0.10). Peacock is the natural red supplier; Alligator and Squid are red demanders.\n- Blue chips: Highly valuable to Alligator (1.00) and Peacock (0.80); moderately low for Squid (0.40). Squid is the natural blue supplier; Alligator (and secondarily Peacock) are blue demanders.\n- Purple chips: Most valuable to Peacock (0.90) and Squid (0.70), low for Alligator (0.20). Alligator is the natural purple supplier; Peacock and Squid are purple demanders.\n- Green chips: Common-value $0.50 to all; they serve as a natural medium of exchange or a low-friction part of multi-step improvements.\n\nBecause players only know their own payoffs, they infer others’ values from chip family description (same ranges) and observed behavior. They know green is common-value, but not how others value red/blue/purple, beyond ranges. Risk: if more than one player accepts a proposal, the recipient is randomized, so proposers can’t target specific partners; this discourages extremely generous but selective offers and nudges them toward acceptable-to-multiple-parties deals or niche offers that only one counterparty finds appealing.\n\nGiven their personas:\n- Squid is structured, cautious, and numbers-aware; he will aim for obviously positive EV trades, initially with small, conservative offers that reveal preferences (e.g., marginally beneficial purple-for-blue trades). He dislikes being exploited, so he rarely accepts ambiguous or borderline trades in early rounds.\n- Alligator is generous and logical; she is willing to give some surplus away if it seems cooperative and efficient, especially when she can turn low-value (to her) purple into high-value red/blue. She is tolerant of unequal outcomes and might offer strong deals to others (e.g., purple plus some green for red/blue) to build a pattern of exchange.\n- Peacock is cooperative but with moderate exploitation caution and norm enforcement; he seeks fair, value-increasing trades and is especially interested in purples and blues while shedding reds. He won’t simply give away value, but he is more willing than Squid to accept modestly favorable-to-other deals if they still benefit him.\n\nOverall, the most plausible dynamic is that: (1) early in the game, players test the waters with modest exchanges to learn which colors others are eager to gain or shed; (2) middle-rounds see more targeted trades with green as a neutral sweetener; (3) by the final round, players try to complete a few higher-leverage restructurings of their portfolios, especially Alligator converting purple into blue/red and Peacock offloading red for purple/blue. Due to the random recipient rule, proposers often design offers where both potential recipients would be at least weakly better off from their own perspective, or at least where the wrong recipient does not devastate the proposer’s payoff.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one coherent path of proposals and accept/decline decisions given these incentives and personalities, assuming reasonably risk-aware but not perfectly Bayesian play, with small-to-moderate trade sizes and some learning from observed responses.",
