ith waiting a round for better opportunities if an early proposal feels ambiguous.\n\nCollectively, players’ prosocial tendencies are present but not extreme: none are strong punishment types, and all tolerate some inequality. The main strategic tension is informational and probabilistic rather than purely distributive. Proposers must design offers that: (1) are profitable given their own values, (2) are not obviously bad for any potential responder (to avoid unanimous rejection), and (3) stay simple enough for risk- and structure-seeking participants to evaluate quickly. Early in the game, proposals will be more exploratory, revealing hints about private valuations (e.g., persistent attempts to buy a specific color). Later rounds incorporate this information: players update beliefs about what others value and adjust their target colors and exchange rates accordingly.\n\nBecause there are only three rounds with one proposal per player per round, each individual turn is significant. A single accepted trade can meaningfully reallocate chips and signal preferences. Expect Ram to push hardest to move out of red and into blue/purple; Goose to seek incremental improvements into blue when possible; and Butterfly to respond opportunistically—accepting modest gains and occasionally initiating trades that exploit perceived overvaluation or undervaluation by others. Nonetheless, coordination is imperfect, and some profitable offers will be declined simply because they are misaligned with at least one responder’s beliefs or because the risk of being the randomly chosen partner in an ambiguous trade feels too high. Over the full game, we see a gradual shift from cautious, learning-oriented offers to more targeted chip-conversion attempts as players converge on what seems attractive to others.",
