pecially if they see prior cooperative moves. With only three rounds and fixed proposer order, players also understand that any chips not profitably traded by the end of round 2 simply convert at their private values, so they will try to execute obviously beneficial exchanges before the game ends. Random recipient selection in the case of multiple acceptances discourages targeted collusion and creates some risk in making widely attractive offers, but this is unlikely to dominate decisions in such a short game.\n\nThe forecast below assumes moderately rational, value-sensitive, but not perfectly calculating behavior, shaped by their prosocial tendencies and desire for structured, mutually beneficial deals. Early proposals are somewhat exploratory and symmetric, with clearer, more value-focused trades emerging in the middle of the game and mild adjustments in the final round.",
