t consider how both potential recipients might respond. This generally discourages extremely generous, one-sided offers aimed at a particular player. Over three rounds, each player proposes once per round, so there are nine proposal opportunities. With short horizon and no communication, players are unlikely to converge fully to the efficient allocation. Instead, we expect a few clearly beneficial trades that move red toward Kangaroo and purple toward Frog, while blue and green serve as payment media. As information accumulates from early offers and acceptances, players may update their beliefs about others’ preferences (for example, inferring that Frog likes purple if Frog eagerly trades away red for purple), but the limited number of turns constrains how much learning can be exploited. Overall, we forecast that: (1) many proposals will be mildly self-serving but not extreme, (2) a subset of clearly good deals (for both sides) will be accepted, especially when they move obviously low-value chips (e.g., Frog’s red) in exchange for obviously high-value chips (e.g., Frog’s purple), and (3) late-round proposals may be either more aggressive (trying to grab last-minute surplus) or more conservative (locking in safe gains with green) depending on who feels ahead or behind.",
