  "game_explanation": "This 3-player, 3-round bargaining game involves trading four chip colors with asymmetric private values for red, blue, and purple, and a common value for green (all $0.50). Each player starts with 10 of each chip type, and each proposal is a simple bilateral trade: request one color, offer another. Proposals are shown to both potential partners, who respond simultaneously; if more than one accepts, a random recipient is chosen. Players know only their own value schedule but can infer others’ likely preferences from what is offered and accepted over time.\n\nIncentives:\n- Zebra values blue and especially purple highly, dislikes red, and sees green as a safe, mid-value asset. Zebra’s best moves convert red into purple or blue, while avoiding giving up purple cheaply. Because zebra is structure-seeking and stability-oriented, we expect measured, value-improving trades and relatively conservative acceptance of trades that worsen his own payoff.\n- Swan is the lowest-valuation player overall: blue is especially weak for him ($0.20), purple and red are $0.40, and green is the same $0.50 as for others. Swan’s rational goal is to turn blue into red/purple or green and to avoid taking on more blue unless paid well. With very high cognitive reflection and stability, he’s likely to behave analytically, resisting obviously negative deals and sometimes accepting modestly negative ones only if they seem strategically informative, but here there’s no future communication benefit; so, expect mostly value-respecting behavior.\n- Dolphin is moderately high on all colors, with red and purple relatively strong ($0.60 and $0.70) and blue somewhat weaker ($0.50). She is prosocial and generosity-forward, which may lead her to accept slightly unfavorable deals that still leave her with good absolute payoffs, especially if the loss is small or hard to compute quickly. Still, she will likely avoid clearly exploitative trades.\n\nKey structural uncertainty:\n- No one knows others’ valuation schedules, but everyone knows: (i) there are differences; (ii) green is common-value. People will interpret trades involving green as more transparent and trades in the colored chips as signals about personal priorities. For example, someone repeatedly offering red for purple probably values purple more than red.\n- Because each round has only one proposal per player and only three rounds in total, there is limited scope for intricate signaling or punishment strategies. Most behavior will be myopic: accept if the trade strictly increases expected total value ex post, decline otherwise, with small noise from social preferences and imperfect calculation.\n\nDynamic expectations:\n- Early in Round 0, players are effectively prior-driven: they treat all non-green chips as plausibly 0.10–1.00 and avoid lopsided trades that obviously risk giving away value. Green is safe, so they’re more willing to lean on it.\n- Across turns within a round, players get weak but growing clues about valuations. For example, if someone eagerly trades away blue for red, observers infer that person finds blue relatively low-value.\n- Zebra, as first proposer in every round, can experiment with slightly aggressive offers, then adjust if they are consistently rejected. Swan and dolphin, acting later, can condition both on zebra’s behavior and on each other’s acceptance patterns.\n\nGiven the personas and payoff structure, the most likely pattern is a small number of clearly positive-sum trades—often using green as the payment chip—and many declined offers that appear too one-sided or ambiguous. Because a random recipient is chosen when multiple players accept, proposers will sometimes design trades attractive to both partners, particularly when selling a chip they personally undervalue (e.g., red for zebra) in exchange for one they strongly prefer (e.g., purple). The forecast below instantiates one cohesive full-game path consistent with these incentives, players’ risk and cooperation tendencies, and the limited time horizon.",
