  "game_explanation": "All three players start with 10 of each chip color: RED, BLUE, PURPLE, and GREEN. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it is a natural medium of exchange and a focal benchmark. The private values make RED extremely valuable to elephant-blue-3237 ($0.90) and least valuable to turtle-pink-5956 ($0.10); BLUE is most valuable to hamster-red-132 ($0.80) and moderately valuable to elephant ($0.60) but low for turtle ($0.20); PURPLE is most valuable to hamster ($0.90), high for turtle ($0.60), and low for elephant ($0.20). This produces classic gains-from-trade opportunities: turtle is relatively happy to part with RED to obtain PURPLE or BLUE; elephant is willing to give up PURPLE to obtain RED; hamster most highly values BLUE and PURPLE and has relatively low value for RED. Given the rule that proposals involve buying one color and selling a different one, players will tend to offer chips they value less in exchange for chips they value more, but they must anticipate that others also protect their own high-value chips.\n\nIncentives: elephant wants to accumulate RED and BLUE and unload PURPLE; hamster wants to accumulate BLUE and PURPLE while being careful about giving up too much of either; turtle wants to convert low-value RED into PURPLE and perhaps BLUE, and is fairly indifferent about holding or using GREEN. Since green is equally valued, trades involving only GREEN versus any other single color are zero-sum in value unless players misperceive or use GREEN to rebalance after earlier trades. Players know only their own value profile, so they infer others’ priorities from which colors they demand and offer across rounds.\n\nUncertainty and dynamics: early in the game, there is informational uncertainty; each player doesn’t know which colors others value most. Proposals serve both as attempts at profitable trade and as signals. Over just three rounds with one turn per player per round (nine total turns), there is some scope for learning but little time for elaborate strategic signaling or reputation building. Turtle is reflective, structure-seeking, and somewhat tolerant of unequal outcomes, so she is likely to make numerically modest, seemingly fair offers aimed at reliable acceptance, while being wary of very lopsided deals but not aggressively punishing them. Hamster is short-horizon and highly guarded against exploitation, so he will avoid trades that look even slightly unfavorable in his own value terms and lean on conservative or tough counteroffers. Elephant is a strong logical reasoner, cooperative, and less exploitation-cautious; he is more willing to engage in trades that yield clear mutual gains and may even accept slightly unfavorable splits if they seem cooperative or if he misjudges values. Across the game, we expect a gradual convergence toward trades that move RED from turtle/hamster to elephant and PURPLE from elephant to hamster/turtle, with GREEN and occasionally BLUE used to balance perceived fairness. Coordination is imperfect, and some mutually beneficial trades will be missed because acceptable price ratios are hard to discover in just a few rounds.",
